ing Vancouver’s Disappeared Women traces “what lives on” from the violent loss of so many women from the same neighbourhood.Dean interrogates representations that aim to humanize the murdered or missing women, asking how these might inadvertently feed into the presumed dehumanization of sex work, Indigeneity, and living in the Downtown Eastside of Vancouver. Taking inspiration from Indigenous women’s research, activism, and art, she challenges readers to reckon with our collective implication in the ongoing violence of settler colonialism and to accept responsibility for addressing its countless injustices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCollective memoryxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aIndigenous womenxViolence againstxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazDowntown-Eastside (Vancouver). 0aIndigenous womenxViolence againstxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aMemorialsxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aMissing persons in artxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aMissing personszBritish ColumbiazDowntown-Eastside (Vancouver)xSocial conditions. 0aMissing personszBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aWomenxViolence againstxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazDowntown-Eastside (Vancouver). 0aWomenxViolence againstxSocial aspectszBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266084740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442660847423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442660847.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles